atogenesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sertoli cells","Leydig cells","Myoid cells","Spermatogonia","Interstitial cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESertoli cells\u003C/strong\u003E are the primary target of FSH in the male reproductive system. These cells line the seminiferous tubules and provide essential support for developing sperm cells. They create the blood-testis barrier and provide nutrients to developing sperm cells.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeydig cells\u003C/strong\u003E are stimulated by luteinising hormone (LH), not FSH, and produce testosterone. \u003Cstrong\u003EMyoid cells\u003C/strong\u003E are contractile cells surrounding the seminiferous tubules. \u003Cstrong\u003ESpermatogonia\u003C/strong\u003E are the stem cells that develop into sperm, but do not directly respond to FSH. \u003Cstrong\u003EInterstitial cells\u003C/strong\u003E is another term for Leydig cells and respond to LH, not FSH.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) stimulates Sertoli cells to support spermatogenesis","Sertoli cells provide structural and nutritional support for developing sperm cells","FSH receptors are found exclusively on Sertoli cells within the seminiferous tubules"],"references":["Makanji Y, Zhu J, Mishra R, Holmquist C, Wong WP, Schwartz NB, Mayo KE, Woodruff TK. Inhibin at 90: from discovery to clinical application, a historical review. Endocr Rev. 2014 Oct;35(5):747-94. doi: 10.1210/er.2014-1003. Epub 2014 Jul 22. PMID: 25051334; PMCID: PMC4167436","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Nette